Part I - Ford GoBike System Data¶

by LongTH¶

Introduction¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a Ford GoBike covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

Ford GoBike is a regional public bicycle sharing system in the San Francisco Bay Area, California. Beginning operation in August 2013 as Bay Area Bike Share, the Ford GoBike system currently has over 2,600 bicycles in 262 stations across San Francisco, East Bay and San Jose. On June 28, 2017, the system officially launched as Ford GoBike in a partnership with Ford Motor Company.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The raw dataset contains 183412 raw records of trips for FordGoBike. Each record has 16 features, which are:

  • duration_sec: The duration of the bike trip in second
  • start_time, end_time: Start and end time of the trip
  • start_station_id, start_station_name, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude: Information about the start station and end station of the trip
  • bike_id: ID of the rented bike
  • user_type: User type - Subcriber or Customer
  • member_birth_year: birth year of the user
  • member_gender: gender of the yser
  • bike_share_for_all_trip: boolean indicates whether a bike share trip was part of the program

Most of them are numerical variables, beside datetime for start_time, end_time and object for station_name, user_type, gender and bike_share_for_all_trip After cleaning some quality issues like missing value and duplicates, the dataset contains 174952 records left.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The feature that I interested in the most is the trip duration, and the relationship between it and other factors

from geopy import distance
def calculate_distance_km(row):
    start_point = (row["start_station_latitude"], row["start_station_longitude"])
    end_point = (row["end_station_latitude"], row["end_station_longitude"])
    return distance.distance(start_point, end_point).km

df["distance_km"] = df.apply(calculate_distance_km, axis=1)
df.head()

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The trip duration distribution looks close to normal distribution. Its peak is concentrated at around 500-700 seconds and then the distribution starts to dip and there is no other peak value.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

There are some unusual in the member_birth_year and location of start and end station of the trip

  • member_birth_year: This feature is converted to member_age by subtracting with the year of this dataset recorded - 2019. After that, there're some outliers like the age is above 100 years old, so I remove those records
  • station location: These features are converted to distance of the trip in kilometers. Hence, I remove trips with very short travelling distance, which are those below 0.1 and trips with very long distance, those greater than 20km.

Multivariate Exploration¶

duration_sec X member_age via start_time_dow¶

In [39]:
def hist2d_duration_age(x, y, **kwargs):
    cmap = kwargs.pop('cmap', None)
    member_age_bins = np.arange(df["member_age"].min(), df["member_age"].max(), 1)
    duration_sec_bins = 10 ** np.arange(np.floor(np.log10(df["duration_sec"]).min()), np.log10(df["duration_sec"]).max() + 0.05, 0.05)
    plt.hist2d(x, y, bins=[member_age_bins, duration_sec_bins], cmap = cmap)
    plt.yscale('log')

g = sns.FacetGrid(data=df, col='start_time_dow', col_wrap=4)
g.map(hist2d_duration_age, 'member_age', 'duration_sec', cmap=None)
plt.colorbar()
g.set_xlabels('Member Age')
g.set_ylabels('Duration (sec)')
